    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-01-pearson-hb-release",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pearson correlation of predicted vs. measured plasma-free haemoglobin release",
      "description": "Pearson r = 0.961 computed across all 5 flow-speed operating points comparing CFD-predicted normalised haemoglobin release rate (g/100 L) against in-vitro photometric measurements on the FDA generic pump. The high correlation coefficient demonstrates strong linear agreement between model and experiment over the tested operating envelope, supporting confidence in the model's ability to track haemolysis trends. This metric is presented as the primary quantitative validation evidence. However, Pearson r measures only the strength of the linear relationship between predicted and observed values; it is insensitive to systematic bias or scale offsets. The COU question requires that the model correctly rank-order operating conditions and confirm that the worst-case RH index remains below 1.0 relative to the predicate device — a determination that depends on absolute magnitude accuracy and correct identification of the maximum, neither of which is captured by a correlation coefficient. A model with a consistently under-predicted haemoglobin release (e.g., 40% lower across all points) would still yield r ≈ 0.96 while falsely satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion.",
      "metricName": "Pearson correlation coefficient (r)",
      "metricValue": "0.961",
      "metricUnit": "dimensionless",
      "validationDataset": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis-dataset",
      "validationScope": "Five operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-02-r2-hb-release",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Coefficient of determination (R²) for haemoglobin release rate predictions",
      "description": "R² = 0.923 computed by regressing CFD-predicted haemoglobin release rates against experimental values across the 5-point operating envelope. The R² value indicates that the model accounts for 92.3% of the variance in measured haemolysis output, which is interpreted as confirming adequate predictive fidelity for the purposes of worst-case identification. While R² is a standard goodness-of-fit metric widely used in biofluid mechanics validation studies, it shares the same fundamental limitation as the Pearson r reported in VR-01: it quantifies variance explained rather than absolute predictive accuracy. The COU requires the model to establish that the worst-case haemolysis index RH does not exceed 1.0 relative to a predicate device. R² does not bound the absolute error at the maximum operating point, does not confirm that the model correctly identifies which of the 5 conditions produces peak haemolysis, and is not monotonically related to the margin by which RH < 1 is satisfied. A model that systematically underestimates peak haemolysis by 25% could still achieve R² > 0.90, creating a false appearance of validation for the specific worst-case identification task.",
      "metricName": "Coefficient of determination (R²)",
      "metricValue": "0.923",
      "metricUnit": "dimensionless",
      "validationDataset": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis-dataset",
      "validationScope": "Five operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-03-rmse-velocity",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "RMSE of impeller-exit velocity magnitude vs. PIV measurements",
      "description": "Root-mean-square error of 0.18 m/s computed between CFD-predicted and PIV-measured velocity magnitude at the impeller exit plane across 312 spatial measurement locations at the nominal design operating point (4 L/min, 3000 RPM). This low RMSE relative to a mean exit velocity of 4.7 m/s (3.8% normalised error) is cited as evidence that the CFD flow field is well-resolved and that the shear stress field driving the haemolysis power-law model is accurately captured. The velocity magnitude RMSE is a credible intermediate indicator of flow-field accuracy; however, haemolysis in centrifugal pumps is primarily driven by peak shear stress exposure time integrated along Lagrangian particle paths, not by the Eulerian velocity magnitude distribution alone. RMSE on velocity magnitude is insensitive to directional errors in the shear stress tensor, recirculation zone extent, and residence time distribution — all of which directly determine the power-law haemolysis index. The COU question (worst-case RH identification) therefore requires validation of the integrated haemolysis index itself, not the intermediate flow-field scalar from which it is derived.",
      "metricName": "Root-mean-square error (RMSE) — velocity magnitude",
      "metricValue": "0.18 m/s",
      "metricUnit": "m/s",
      "validationDataset": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-cfd-output-5-operating-points",
      "validationScope": "312-point PIV measurement plane at impeller exit, nominal operating point"
    }
  ],
